---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "AES Dividend Analysis & History",
  description: "Can this major utility provider fuel your passive income strategy? We've analyzed their latest dividend payout and 5-year growth trajectory to find out.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "Article",
      "headline": "AES Dividend Analysis & History",
      "description": meta.description,
      "datePublished": meta.published,
      "author": {
        "@type": "Organization",
        "name": "Westmount Fundamentals"
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Are AES stocks a good dividend investment?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "AES Corporation offers an attractive dividend yield currently hovering near 5%, making it an appealing option for income-seeking investors looking for exposure to the utility and renewable energy sectors."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the AES dividend yield?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The AES dividend yield is approximately 4.96%, supported by a quarterly payout structure and a manageable payout ratio around 54%."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How often does AES pay dividends?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "AES pays dividends on a quarterly basis, typically distributing payments in February, May, August, and November."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Has AES consistently increased its dividend?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, AES has shown a commitment to consistent dividend increases. Over the past five years, the quarterly dividend has grown steadily from $0.158 in 2021 to $0.176 in 2026."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the risks of investing in AES stocks for dividends?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Key risks include regulatory changes, fluctuating energy prices, and the massive capital expenditures required for their transition toward renewable energy, which could potentially strain cash flow and impact future dividend growth."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/aes-stocks" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content container">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>AES Dividend Analysis & History</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">A comprehensive breakdown of The AES Corporation's dividend yield, payout history, and utility sector positioning.</p>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2>Current Dividend Yield and Payout Info</h2>
      <p>For income investors evaluating utility stocks, The AES Corporation (AES) stands out as a prominent player transitioning into renewable energy while maintaining shareholder returns. If you are researching "aes stocks" for passive income, the current metrics are highly relevant.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Key Dividend Metrics</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dividend Yield:</strong> ~4.96%</li>
          <li><strong>Current Quarterly Payout:</strong> $0.176 per share</li>
          <li><strong>Annualized Payout:</strong> $0.704 per share</li>
          <li><strong>Payout Frequency:</strong> Quarterly</li>
          <li><strong>Payout Ratio:</strong> ~53.7%</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p>The dividend yield of nearly 5% is competitive within the utilities sector. The moderate payout ratio of 53.7% indicates that the dividend is well-covered by earnings, leaving the company with sufficient capital to fund its transition toward sustainable energy infrastructure.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>5-Year Dividend History</h2>
      <p>A reliable indicator of a company's financial health and commitment to shareholders is its dividend track record. AES has consistently paid and grown its dividend over recent years.</p>

      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Ex-Dividend Date</th>
            <th>Amount ($)</th>
            <th>Frequency</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Jan 30, 2026</td>
            <td>0.176</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Oct 31, 2025</td>
            <td>0.176</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Nov 01, 2024</td>
            <td>0.173</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Oct 31, 2023</td>
            <td>0.166</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Oct 26, 2022</td>
            <td>0.158</td>
            <td>Quarterly</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p>This historical consistency is exactly what income investors look for when stabilizing a portfolio against market volatility.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Dividend Growth Rate Analysis</h2>
      <p>Analyzing the past five years reveals that AES is not just maintaining its payout but actively growing it. The quarterly dividend has increased from $0.158 in 2022 to $0.176 in early 2026. This represents a steady, methodical growth rate aimed at keeping pace with or slightly exceeding historical inflation rates, protecting the purchasing power of the income generated for investors.</p>
      <p>The company's ability to maintain this growth relies heavily on its execution of capital-intensive renewable energy projects and the regulatory environment across its global footprint.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Key Metrics & Company Profile</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Sector:</strong> Utilities</li>
          <li><strong>Trailing P/E Ratio:</strong> 10.84</li>
          <li><strong>Forward P/E Ratio:</strong> 5.95</li>
          <li><strong>Business Summary:</strong> Operates power generation and utility businesses globally with a strategic pivot toward renewable energy and energy storage solutions.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p>The low forward P/E ratio suggests that the market may be undervaluing AES relative to its projected earnings, or it is pricing in the risks associated with global utility operations and the heavy debt loads typical of the sector. However, for a yield-focused investor, a lower valuation coupled with a safe payout ratio can present an attractive entry point.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Comparison to Category Average</h2>
      <p>The utility sector typically averages a dividend yield between 3.0% and 4.0%. At nearly 5%, AES offers a premium yield compared to many of its peers. While not as high as some specialized income funds (such as those covered in our <a href="/high-yield-dividend-etf-passive-income">HIGH ETF Analysis</a>), it provides a balance of yield and fundamental utility-sector stability.</p>
      <p>Unlike pure growth plays in the energy space (see our <a href="/oklo-stocks">OKLO Analysis</a>), AES provides immediate, tangible returns to shareholders via its dividend policy.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Interactive Dividend Reinvestment Calculator</h2>
      <p>Use the calculator below to project your potential passive income from an investment in AES based on current parameters.</p>

      <div class="card" id="calcContainer" data-initialized="false">
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="shares" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Shares Owned:</label>
          <input type="number" id="shares" value="1000" min="1" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="sharePrice" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Share Price ($):</label>
          <input type="number" id="sharePrice" value="14.20" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
          <label for="yield" style="display:block; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; font-weight: 600;">Dividend Yield (%):</label>
          <input type="number" id="yield" value="4.96" step="0.01" style="width: 100%; padding: 0.5rem; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 4px; background: var(--bg-color); color: var(--text-primary);" />
        </div>
        <div style="margin-top: 1.5rem; padding-top: 1rem; border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);">
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Projected Annual Income: <span id="projectedIncome" style="color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.25rem;">$704.32</span></h4>
          <h4 style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Quarterly Payout: <span id="projectedQuarterly" style="color: var(--accent-color); font-size: 1.1rem;">$176.08</span></h4>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>Are AES stocks a good dividend investment?</summary>
        <p>AES Corporation offers an attractive dividend yield currently hovering near 5%, making it an appealing option for income-seeking investors looking for exposure to the utility and renewable energy sectors.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is the AES dividend yield?</summary>
        <p>The AES dividend yield is approximately 4.96%, supported by a quarterly payout structure and a manageable payout ratio around 54%.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How often does AES pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>AES pays dividends on a quarterly basis, typically distributing payments in February, May, August, and November.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Has AES consistently increased its dividend?</summary>
        <p>Yes, AES has shown a commitment to consistent dividend increases. Over the past five years, the quarterly dividend has grown steadily from $0.158 in 2021 to $0.176 in 2026.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What are the risks of investing in AES stocks for dividends?</summary>
        <p>Key risks include regulatory changes, fluctuating energy prices, and the massive capital expenditures required for their transition toward renewable energy, which could potentially strain cash flow and impact future dividend growth.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    function initAesCalculator() {
      const container = document.getElementById('calcContainer');
      if (!container || container.dataset.initialized === 'true') return;

      const sharesInput = document.getElementById('shares');
      const priceInput = document.getElementById('sharePrice');
      const yieldInput = document.getElementById('yield');
      const incomeOutput = document.getElementById('projectedIncome');
      const quarterlyOutput = document.getElementById('projectedQuarterly');

      if (!sharesInput || !priceInput || !yieldInput || !incomeOutput || !quarterlyOutput) return;

      function updateCalc() {
        const shares = parseFloat(sharesInput.value) || 0;
        const price = parseFloat(priceInput.value) || 0;
        const yieldPct = parseFloat(yieldInput.value) || 0;

        const totalValue = shares * price;
        const annualIncome = totalValue * (yieldPct / 100);
        const quarterlyIncome = annualIncome / 4;

        incomeOutput.textContent = '$' + annualIncome.toFixed(2);
        quarterlyOutput.textContent = '$' + quarterlyIncome.toFixed(2);
      }

      sharesInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      priceInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);
      yieldInput.addEventListener('input', updateCalc);

      container.dataset.initialized = 'true';
    }

    document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', initAesCalculator);
    document.addEventListener('astro:page-load', initAesCalculator);
  </script>

  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    th, td { padding: 0.75rem 1rem; text-align: left; border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    th { font-weight: 600; color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 0.85rem; text-transform: uppercase; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
